<P>
WALSH LEADS CARSON PAST LYNWOOD, 37-14 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID RAATZ 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
John Walsh tied a school record by passing for four touchdowns and leading 
Carson High to a 37-14 victory over Lynwood Friday night in an intersectional 
game at Lynwood. 
</P>
<P>
The Colts' victory was the 300th for Coach Gene Vollnogle, who will retire 
after the season. 
</P>
<P>
The winningest coach in California history, Vollnogle has won 279 games at the 
varsity level. 
</P>
<P>
Carson improved to 2-0 and Lynwood dropped to 1-2. 
</P>
<P>
Walsh struggled in the first half, completing four of 10 with two 
interceptions. But on the first drive of the second half, he passed to running 
back Abdul Muhammad on a 55-yard touchdown scoring play to give Carson a 17-0 
lead. It was the first of Muhammad's three touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
Walsh finished with 12 completions in 22 attempts for 337 yards. Among Carson's 
defensive standouts were back Tarriel Hopper (two fumble recoveries) and 
lineman Art Malupe (two sacks). 
</P>
<P>
Carson, the top-rated team in the City, took a 24-0 lead late in the third 
quarter when Muhammad caught a 14-yard touchdown pass. Colt running back Darryl 
Gideon had a 47-yard run to set up Muhammad's second touchdown. DAVID RAATZ 
</P>
