<P>
WINLESS LONG BEACH PLAYS HOST TO PACIFIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DICK WAGNER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
George Allen, still winless in his return as a college football coach, tries 
again today at 1 p.m. when Cal State Long Beach plays University of the Pacific 
in Veterans Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
The Big West Conference game will be the home opener for the 49ers, who are 0-3 
overall and 0-1 in the league. 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach, which lost last week to San Diego State, 38-20, has committed 10 
turnovers and given up an average of 41 points a game. 
</P>
<P>
"I think each game we're getting better," Allen said. "We just have to 
eliminate all these mistakes." 
</P>
<P>
The 49er offense has relied on quarterback Todd Studer and wide receiver Mark 
Seay. Of Studer's 35 successful passes, 14 have been caught by Seay for 199 
yards. 
</P>
<P>
Pacific (1-2, 0-1) also is pass-oriented. In a 28-14 loss last week to San Jose 
State, the Tigers were thrown for minus-one yard rushing, but quarterback Kris 
King passed for 282 yards. DICK WAGNER 
