<HEADLINE>
<P>
ARAB MOB BURNS ISRAELI SOLDIER TO DEATH FOLLOWING CAR ACCIDENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
JERUSALEM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An angry mob of Arab refugees stoned and burned an Israeli reserve soldier to 
death after his car struck two Palestinian teen-agers in a refugee camp, the 
army said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
The soldier, who was not identified, had driven his car by mistake into the 
Bureij refugee camp at about 11 a.m. Thursday when the streets were full of 
shoppers, an army spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
Palestinian youths immediately stoned the civilian car, which had yellow 
Israeli license plates. The soldier, who was in uniform, tried to escape and 
accidentally hit a donkey cart, injuring two Arab brothers riding on it, the 
spokesman and Palestinian sources said. 
</P>
<P>
"The accident caused severe rioting in the location," the spokesman said. "The 
car was stoned with rocks. The driver was injured, and the vehicle was set on 
fire." 
</P>
<P>
The slaying occurred on the start of Jewish New Year, Rosh Hashanah, a national 
and religious holiday when most places of business and entertainment are 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Israeli politicians on the right and left condemned the attack. 
Agriculture Minister Rafael Eitan, head of the right-wing Tsomet Party, was 
quoted by Israel Radio as saying, "The army should wipe from the surface of the 
earth all the houses near the scene of the murder. I'll suggest it at Sunday's 
Cabinet meeting." 
</P>
<P>
Several Parliament members said the brutal slaying showed the intifada, or Arab 
uprising, is not finished. Shevah Weiss, a member of the center-left opposition 
Labor Party, called the killing "a victory for the extremists," adding it 
showed the depth of hatred motivating Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the car was set on fire, soldiers arrived and dispersed the 
crowd, Palestinian sources said. Bureij camp, home to more than 16,000 
Palestinians, was placed under curfew and the Gaza Strip declared a closed 
military zone, preventing journalists from entering. 
</P>
<P>
The military censor held up publication of the incident for more than 21 hours 
while the soldier's family was notified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
